00:15:16.373 --> 00:15:19.165
Patient comes in, "Yeah, I think I'm 20 weeks."

324
00:15:19.165 --> 00:15:21.732
"Okay, we're gonna go ahead and get it today,"

325
00:15:21.732 --> 00:15:23.139
or let's say 18 weeks.

326
00:15:23.139 --> 00:15:27.030
But you know, in the end, she turns out to be nine weeks.

327
00:15:27.030 --> 00:15:28.770
Okay, so you'd have to recalculate it

328
00:15:28.770 --> 00:15:31.497
or draw it when she's 16 to 18 weeks, in that case.

329
00:15:31.497 --> 00:15:34.113
Now, the aneuploidies,

330
00:15:36.242 --> 00:15:39.603
this is typically done now with what's called cell-free DNA.

331
00:15:40.506 --> 00:15:42.857
All pregnant women get this done.

332
00:15:42.857 --> 00:15:46.020
Typically, it's done somewhere between 11 and 13 weeks

333
00:15:46.020 --> 00:15:48.999
and it's done regardless of maternal age.

334
00:15:48.999 --> 00:15:51.240
So you can do first-trimester screening,

335
00:15:51.240 --> 00:15:53.232
you can do quadruple screening in the second trimester,

336
00:15:53.232 --> 00:15:54.605
you can do integrated screening,

337
00:15:54.605 --> 00:15:56.100
first and second trimesters.

338
00:15:56.100 --> 00:15:58.530
These are all the possibilities.

339
00:15:58.530 --> 00:16:00.960
Just know, everybody gets offered screening

340
00:16:00.960 --> 00:16:01.793
for aneuploidies.

341
00:16:01.793 --> 00:16:05.496
I think that would be the question on the exam, okay?

342
00:16:05.496 --> 00:16:09.720
Now, if we look at screening, we've gone to cell-free DNA

343
00:16:09.720 --> 00:16:11.790
because it's the most sensitive and specific

344
00:16:11.790 --> 00:16:13.833
for the common fetal aneuploidies.

345
00:16:14.976 --> 00:16:18.866
This is combined with an ultrasound at 18 to 22 weeks,

346
00:16:18.866 --> 00:16:23.493
which we would consider our screening or anatomic survey.

347
00:16:28.290 --> 00:16:29.123
Okay.

348
00:16:30.495 --> 00:16:33.000
According to the CDC, all women of childbearing age

349
00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:35.790
